(41, 14, 36, 58, 5, 7, 8, 'not what I will, but what thou wilt', 'Connection of Suffering and Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of suffering and submission to God''s will. In Mark, Jesus expresses a desire to avoid suffering while ultimately submitting to the Father''s will, paralleling Hebrews, where Jesus learns obedience through his suffering.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 36, 43, 12, 27, 27, 'take away this cup from me', 'Connection of Troubled Souls', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of inner turmoil faced by Jesus as he approaches his impending suffering. The phrases ''save me from this hour'' and ''take away this cup from me'' reflect a deep emotional struggle with the path ahead, while ultimately submitting to the Father''s will.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 36, 41, 10, 27, 27, 'all things are possible unto thee', 'Possibility with God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God''s omnipotence. In Mark 14:36, Jesus acknowledges that ''all things are possible'' for God, while Mark 10:27 states that with God, ''all things are possible.'' This connection highlights the assurance of divine capability in challenging circumstances.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 36, 50, 2, 8, 8, 'not what I will, but what thou wilt', 'Obedience in Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience in the face of suffering. In Mark, Jesus expresses his desire for the cup to be taken away, yet submits to the Father''s will, while Philippians emphasizes his obedience unto death.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 40, 26, 40, 40, 'couldest not thou watch one hour', 'Disciples'' Sleep During Vigil', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' failure to stay awake while Jesus prayed. The direct address to Peter about watching for one hour is a key parallel in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 10, 16, 17, 17, 'sleepest thou', 'Sleep and Friendship Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of loyalty and vigilance in relationships. In both passages, the expectation of being present and attentive to friends is emphasized, whether in the context of watching or supporting them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 40, 25, 5, 5, 'sleepest thou? couldest not thou watch', 'Sleep and Vigilance Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sleep during critical moments. In Mark, Peter is admonished for sleeping while Jesus asks for vigilance, while in Matthew, all the bridesmaids sleep while waiting for the bridegroom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 41, 14, 29, 31, 'couldest not thou watch one hour?', 'Peter''s Weakness and Denial', 'This connection highlights Peter''s inability to stay awake in the garden, paralleling his earlier boastful claim of unwavering loyalty. Both passages emphasize Peter''s struggle with faithfulness in critical moments.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 41, 14, 40, 41, 'couldest not thou watch one hour?', 'Disciples'' Sleep and Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' inability to stay awake during a critical moment. The repeated mention of their sleep highlights their unpreparedness for the impending betrayal of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 42, 9, 31, 32, 'sleepest thou? couldest not thou watch', 'Sleep and Awareness in Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sleep affecting the disciples'' awareness during significant moments. In Mark, Peter is questioned for sleeping while Jesus prays, and in Luke, Peter and others are described as ''heavy with sleep'' during a revelation of Jesus'' glory.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 37, 42, 22, 45, 46, 'sleepest thou? couldest not thou watch', 'Disciples Sleeping in Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' failure to stay awake during a critical moment of prayer. They highlight the theme of spiritual vigilance and the consequences of succumbing to sleep instead of remaining alert.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 40, 26, 41, 41, NULL, 'Connection of Temptation and Weakness', 'Both passages emphasize the need to ''watch and pray'' to avoid temptation, highlighting the contrast between the willing spirit and the weak flesh. This thematic parallel underscores a shared message about vigilance in spiritual matters.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 40, 24, 42, 42, 'Watch ye and pray', 'Call to Vigilance and Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being watchful. Mark 14:38 warns against temptation, while Matthew 24:42 urges vigilance for the Lord''s return.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 42, 21, 36, 36, 'Watch ye and pray', 'Connection of Vigilance and Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of watching and praying to avoid temptation and to be prepared for future events. They highlight the need for spiritual readiness in the face of challenges.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 42, 22, 40, 40, 'enter into temptation', 'Connection on Temptation and Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prayer to avoid temptation. Mark highlights the weakness of the flesh, while Luke directly instructs to pray to not enter temptation.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 45, 7, 18, 25, 'the flesh is weak', 'Connection of Human Weakness', 'Both passages emphasize the struggle between the spirit and the flesh. Mark highlights the weakness of the flesh, while Romans elaborates on the conflict within, showing the inability to perform good despite the desire to do so.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 66, 3, 2, 3, 'watch ye and pray', 'Call to Vigilance and Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being watchful and prepared against temptation. Mark highlights the weakness of the flesh, while Revelation warns of the consequences of failing to watch.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 38, 48, 5, 17, 17, 'the flesh is weak', 'Conflict of Spirit and Flesh', 'Both passages emphasize the struggle between the spirit and the flesh. Mark highlights the weakness of the flesh, while Galatians describes the opposing desires of the flesh and the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 39, 40, 26, 42, 44, NULL, 'Prayer and Repetition in Gethsemane', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' repeated prayers in the Garden of Gethsemane. The phrase ''went away again'' highlights his persistence in seeking the Father''s will.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 39, 40, 6, 7, 7, 'spake the same words', 'Prayer and Repetition', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Jesus'' earnest prayer and the warning against vain repetitions. Both passages emphasize the nature of prayer, suggesting that sincerity is more important than mere repetition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 39, 47, 12, 8, 8, 'spake the same words', 'Prayer and Repetition in Distress', 'Both passages emphasize the act of praying multiple times in moments of distress. In Mark, Jesus prays ''the same words'' again, while Paul ''besought the Lord thrice'' for relief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 39, 42, 18, 1, 1, 'prayed, and spake the same words', 'Connection of Prayer and Persistence', 'This connection highlights the importance of prayer in both passages. Mark emphasizes Jesus'' repeated prayer, while Luke encourages continual prayer without losing heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 40, 1, 44, 16, 16, 'neither wist they what to answer him', 'Sleep and Inaction in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the theme of inaction in moments of crisis. In Mark, the disciples are found asleep, unable to respond, while in Genesis, Judah expresses uncertainty about how to respond to their predicament.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 40, 41, 9, 33, 34, 'neither wist they what to answer him', 'Disputes and Sleepiness', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of awareness among the disciples. In Mark 14:40, they are asleep and do not know how to respond, while in Mark 9:33-34, they are silent about their dispute, indicating a disconnect from Jesus'' teachings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 40, 45, 3, 19, 19, 'neither wist they what to answer him', 'Human Weakness and Accountability', 'This connection highlights human frailty in both passages. In Mark, the disciples'' inability to stay awake reflects a broader theme of human weakness, while Romans emphasizes the universal guilt of humanity under the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 41, 41, 9, 31, 31, 'the Son of man is betrayed', 'Connection of Betrayal and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the betrayal of the Son of man. In Mark 14:41, he is betrayed into the hands of sinners, while in Mark 9:31, he is delivered into the hands of men to be killed.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 41, 41, 14, 35, 35, 'the hour is come', 'Connection of Jesus'' Hour', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the hour'' in relation to Jesus'' impending betrayal and suffering. In Mark 14:35, Jesus prays for the hour to pass, while in Mark 14:41, he acknowledges that the hour has come.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 41, 43, 17, 1, 1, 'the hour is come', 'Connection of the Hour', 'Both passages emphasize ''the hour is come,'' indicating a pivotal moment in Jesus'' mission. This connection highlights the transition from impending betrayal to the glorification of the Son.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 41, 7, 10, 14, 14, 'betrayed into the hands of sinners', 'Betrayal and Deliverance Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and the call for deliverance in times of trouble. In Mark, the Son of Man is betrayed, while in Judges, the people are urged to seek deliverance from their chosen gods during tribulation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 14, 41, 11, 18, 27, 27, 'sleep on now, and take your rest', 'Sleep and Wakefulness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sleep, with Mark highlighting the disciples'' physical rest and Elijah''s mocking of the prophets'' god who ''sleepeth.'' This connection highlights the contrast between human rest and divine awareness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
